!!【柯林斯英汉双解大词典】

:<div>

jeer /dʒɪə/

(jeering,jeered,jeers) 

1. V-T/V-I To jeer at someone means to say or shout rude and insulting things to them to show that you do not like or respect them. 嘲弄 

例： Marchers jeered at white passers-by, but there was no violence, nor any arrests. 游行者们嘲弄路过的白人们，但并没有发生暴力事件，也没人被逮捕。 

例： Demonstrators jeered the mayor as he arrived for a week-long visit. 示威者们在市长到达进行为期一周访问的时候嘲弄了他。 

2. jeering N-UNCOUNT 嘲弄 

例： There was constant jeering and interruption from the floor. 议员席上不时有嘲笑和打岔。 

3. N-COUNT Jeers are rude and insulting things that people shout to show they do not like or respect someone. 奚落人的话 

例： ...the heckling and jeers of his audience. …观众对他的那些诘问和奚落。

</div>

